This paper discusses the impact of adversarial attacks on Deep Neural Networks (DNNs) and proposes a methodology to evaluate defense mechanisms against such attacks. The paper also proposes a new defense mechanism called Randomly Perturbed Ensemble Neural Networks (RPENNs). Given the focus on DNNs and adversarial attacks, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses security and cryptography-related concepts, which makes cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely sub-category. The paper uses image classification as an example, which suggests cs.CV (Computer Vision) as another possible sub-category. The paper proposes a new defense mechanism, which falls under the scope of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper evaluates the defense mechanisms using the ILSVRC2012 validation dataset, which suggests cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as another possible sub-category.
